New update: I am simplifying the problem by assuming a constant probability per state of having more cases in September than in June. Then all the probabilities are derived from combining the per-state probabilities (really easy because the combination results in a binomial distribution). The problem is estimating the per-state probability of increase in cases. I actually have run two scenarios, p = 0.25 and p = 0.5 (25 and 50% respectively), which yield: buckets25 = {0, 25, 71, 4, 0, 0, 0}
buckets50 = {0, 0, 2, 48, 48, 2, 0} Then I assume a probability for each of the two per-state probabilities: 66% for buckets25 and 34% for buckets50. This choice is driven by the observation that cases in June are likely to be really high, so at first sight it seems it is more probable that the number of states with more cases will be smaller in September than in June. Notice that @Dillyweed estimates a higher probability [1], and @Bobbiekar52 pointed out the fact that schools reopen in September [2]. These two points of view make me thing that I am underestimating the per-state probability in my current prediction. Yet we are but at the beginning. [1] https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1063860
[2] https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1066772
